<br>
From your source:<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> Deep in the air, there might be problems from harm of the crew by gamma scattering.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
This is part of what I’ve been saying all along.<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr>  Freeman Dyson, an early worker on the project, estimated that with conventional nuclear weapons, each launch would cause fatal cancers in ten human beings from the fallout. To keep this in perspective, roughly 600 people die of cancer each year form eating spices.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
It’s so nice that Dyson put things into perspective and was willing to accept these losses. What else was he willing to accept to achieve his goals, I wonder?<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> The launch of such a craft from the ground or from low Earth orbit would generate an electromagnetic pulse that could cause significant damage to computers and satellites, as well as flooding the van Allen belts with high-energy radiation.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Interesting, it would flood the van Allen belts with high-energy radiation but was presumed perfectly safe for the crew and ship.<br>
<br>
From the link provided earlier regarding the so-called “plumbbob test.”<br>
<br>
<!--EZCODE QUOTE START--><blockquote><strong><em>Quote:</em></strong><hr> A velocity of 6 times Earth's escape velocity (67 km/sec, since escape velocity is 11.2 km/sec) would give the plate a kinetic energy 60% larger than the total energy released by the explosion. This is clearly impossible.<br>
<br>
Dr. Brownlee points that they were aware at the time that was not credible that the plate might actually might escape from Earth. Leaving aside whether such an extremely hypersonic unaerodynamic object could even survive passage through the lower atmosphere, it is impossible for it to retain much of its initial velocity while passing through the atmosphere A ground launched hypersonic projectile has the same problem with maintaining its velocity that an incoming meteor has.<br>
<br>
Of course the fact that the projectile was not found is no proof of a successful space launch. The cylinder and cover plate of Pascal-A were also not found, even though no hypersonic projectile was involved. Even speeds typical of ordinary artillery can send an object many kilometers, beyond the area of any reasonable search effort.<hr></blockquote><!--EZCODE QUOTE END--><br>
<br>
Plenty of hand waving with no substance.<br>
